        "excerpt": "I have seen that every labor and every skill which is done is the result of rivalry between a man and his neighbor. This too is vanity and striving after wind.",
        "body": "Verse 4 is the chapter's most penetrating psychological claim, and its comprehensiveness — 'every labor and every skill' — should not be softened. The Preacher is not describing only the obviously competitive or the manifestly jealous. He is issuing a diagnostic verdict about the motivational structure of ordinary human achievement. The word qinah covers the semantic range from passionate zeal (as in God's 'jealousy' for Israel, Ezekiel 39:25) to corrosive envy (as in the envy of Proverbs 27:4: 'jealousy is cruel as Sheol'). Here the context — 'between a man and his neighbor' — tilts decisively toward competitive envy: I work harder because he has more than I do.\n\nThis is not a condemnation of excellence or of work itself. Ecclesiastes commends diligent work elsewhere (9:10: 'Whatever your hand finds to do, do it with all your might'). The problem is not the labor but the engine. A man may build a brilliant company, cultivate exceptional skill, or produce genuinely beautiful work — and the engine driving all of it may be the neighbor's success that he cannot bear. The Preacher's verdict is that work thus motivated, however productive its output, belongs to the category of hevel: insubstantial, ultimately empty.\n\nThe corrective of verses 5-6 is the chapter's most carefully balanced pair. Verse 5 refuses to endorse the opposite of frantic rivalry — idle folly is not wisdom but self-consumption. 'Consumes his own flesh' is visceral: the fool who folds his hands is not peacefully resting but actively devouring himself through inaction. Verse 6 then points to the narrow path between them: one handful with nachat (rest, ease, tranquility) beats two fists of amal and wind. The tov-min saying commends sufficiency, not sloth. Contentment with enough — rather than the compulsive pursuit of more that comparison with a neighbor produces — is the Preacher's practical wisdom for the corrupted motive.\n\nPhilippians 4:11-12 (Paul's 'I have learned, in whatever state I am, to be content') is the New Testament's most precise canonical parallel. Paul's contentment is explicitly learned — it is the achieved posture of one whose reference point has shifted from the neighbor's resources to Christ's sufficiency. Ecclesiastes 4:6 maps the problem Paul's contentment solves.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Qinah* (envy/rivalry, 4:4) is the same noun used for God's jealous zeal in Ezekiel 39:25 and for the cruelty of jealousy in Song of Songs 8:6. *Nachat* (rest/tranquility, 4:6) is distinct from *shabbat* (cessation) — it implies peaceful enjoyment of what one has, not mere inactivity."
