        "body": "The companionship unit (4:9-12) is the chapter's only sustained positive argument, and its placement — between the second vanity verdict (4:8) and the political parable (4:13-16) — is rhetorically deliberate. The Preacher has just described the man whose eyes are never satisfied; now he describes the structural alternative, not as an emotional or spiritual uplift but as a functional argument. Two are better than one **because** they produce better results. The because (ki) is significant: the Preacher is not appealing to sentiment but to logic.\n\nThe three illustrations that follow — falling and being lifted (4:10), cold and being warmed (4:11), overpowered and being defended (4:12) — form a deliberate sequence that moves from accident to discomfort to aggression. The progression is important: companionship is most valuable when conditions are worst. In prosperity, solitude may feel adequate; in mishap, cold, or attack, the alone person is exposed at every point. The Preacher is making the case that human vulnerability is comprehensive and that community is the only structural response to it.\n\nThe three-strand cord of verse 12 is the unit's climactic image. Scholars including Tremper Longman, Roland Murphy, and Douglas Stuart note that the transition from two to three is not explained within the text — no third party is identified. The homiletical tradition that reads the third strand as God, Christ, or the Holy Spirit is interpretively attractive but goes beyond what Qoheleth states. What Qoheleth states is mathematically and practically sufficient for his argument: the surplus resilience of a third strand over two exceeds what would be predicted by linear addition. Three-stranded rope is exponentially harder to break than two-stranded rope for reasons of braid geometry — the Preacher is appealing to a well-known craft observation to make a relational point.\n\nIn canonical context, the three-strand cord points beyond itself even if the text does not supply the referent. The New Testament community of the body of Christ (1 Corinthians 12:12-27) is precisely a multi-stranded interdependence where the suffering of one affects all, the honor of one benefits all, and the strength of the whole exceeds the sum of its parts. The Preacher's empirical case for companionship becomes, in the New Testament, a theological account of why the local church exists as the primary context for Christian formation.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chaver* (companion, 4:10) — associate, fellow, one bound by covenant-like relationship; used in Malachi 2:14 for the marriage covenant. *Chut* (cord, 4:12) — thread, string, strand; the same word for the scarlet thread of Rahab (Joshua 2:18), whose three-dimensional significance in the text of Joshua is similarly left for the reader to interpret."
