        "title": "The political parable — wisdom displaced by ingratitude, legacy swallowed by vanity",
        "range": "4:13-16",
        "excerpt": "A poor yet wise lad is better than an old and foolish king who no longer knows how to receive instruction... even the ones who will come later will not be happy with him, for this too is vanity and striving after wind.",
        "body": "The chapter's closing parable is its most compressed and most ambiguous. The Preacher narrates a three-act story: a wise youth rises from prison to throne (4:13-14), crowds throng to support him (4:15), and future crowds refuse to celebrate him (4:16). The movement from prison to palace to popular abandon covers the full arc of political ambition in seven verses. Several commentators (Iain Provan, Craig Bartholomew) have noted the structural parallel to Joseph — the wise youth imprisoned and then elevated — but the Preacher deliberately withholds the name and the divine providence that makes Joseph's story redemptive. What remains when divine providence is removed from the Joseph-pattern is precisely the vanity of 4:16: even the wisest and most providentially positioned leader will be forgotten.\n\nThe parable's theological edge is in what the old king has lost: not power (he still has it) but the capacity to receive instruction (4:13). The Hebrew zahar means to be warned, admonished, cautioned. The foolish king's folly is not stupidity but unteachability — he has arrived at a stage where correction no longer reaches him. This is Proverbs 12:1 made narrative: 'Whoever loves discipline loves knowledge, but he who hates reproof is stupid.' The wise youth, by contrast, is defined not by his wisdom in isolation but by the fact that wisdom can still enter and reshape him.\n\nJonathan Edwards, in his Religious Affections, identified the teachable heart — the heart open to God's correcting word — as one of the most reliable marks of genuine spiritual life. The old king's unteachability is Ecclesiastes' portrait of what spiritual hardening looks like in the political sphere. It is the same phenomenon as the pharaoh of Exodus, the heart that has hardened until even catastrophic pressure cannot open it.\n\nThe crowd's transience (4:15-16) closes the chapter's final argument against the vanity of legacy. No achievement — not wisdom, not poverty-to-throne ascent, not popular acclaim — secures lasting honor under the sun. The 'no end to all the people' of verse 16 is deliberately ironic: the crowd is endless, but its loyalty is momentary. Each new generation of observers arrives, celebrates, and then refuses to be satisfied by what it has inherited. This is the social equivalent of the eyes that are never satisfied in 4:8 — insatiability operates at the collective level as much as at the individual level. The only corrective the Preacher has prepared the reader to receive is found at the book's structural hinge in 5:1-7: 'Guard your steps as you go to the house of God... for God is in heaven and you are on the earth.' The fear of God is the chapter's implicit answer to every vanity it names."
